{
  format: 1
  name: projected-base-bypasses-projection-in-temporal-read
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#views", "§7.1", "#buckets", "§14.1", "§14.2"]
  tags: ["temporal", "authz", "boundary", "regression"]
  note: '''A temporal read whose base is a PROJECTED bucketed collection DROPS the
    projection: `.coll{ field }.$at(t)` returns EVERY extant row of `coll` active at
    t in its FULL, unprojected shape — every declared field, including ones the
    projection was meant to hide. This is the projection twin of the filter-bypass
    (filtered-base-bypasses-predicate-in-temporal-read): both share the same root in
    `RuntimeEnv::working_set` discarding the evaluated base and ranging the selector
    over the collection`s full extant.

    eb380ec made `bind_name_of` (crates/liasse-expr/src/eval/views.rs) recurse
    through `Project`, so a PROJECTED base `.records{ label }` yields
    `base_name = Some("records")`. `eval_temporal` evaluates the base into the
    correctly PROJECTED rows (only `label`), then the environment`s working_set,
    seeing `base_name = Some`, returns the collection`s FULL extant rows and applies
    only the temporal activity rule — the projection never runs against the working
    set, so the hidden `secret` field leaks in every returned row.

    §7.1: a view ranges over the collection it NAMES and a projection RESHAPES its
    rows to the chosen outputs. §14.1: `.$at(t)` selects the rows active at t. The
    composition `.records{ label }.$at(t)` is therefore the records rows active at t,
    each RESHAPED to just `{ label }` — never the full record. Returning the hidden
    `secret` is a §7.1/§14.1 violation and a data-over-exposure.

    Setup: one lifecycle bucket `records` with two rows, both on the interval
    [2025-06-01, 2027-01-01), so both are ACTIVE at the 2026-01-01 clock and at the
    2026-03-15 read. Each row carries a `label` (the projected, exposed field) and a
    `secret` (the field the projection drops).

    Step 1 (control, bare temporal, full shape): `.records.$at(t){ label, secret }`
    shows BOTH fields of BOTH rows, proving the rows are extant, active at t, and
    that `secret` is present in the underlying extant.

    Step 2 (control, plain projection, NON-temporal): `.records{ label }` returns
    rows with ONLY `label`, proving the projection reshapes correctly in the
    ordinary (non-working_set) evaluation path.

    Step 3 (bug, projected temporal): `.records{ label }.$at(t)` MUST return the
    active rows reshaped to `{ label }` only. The runtime returns the full extant
    rows (including `secret`) because working_set ranges the selector over records`
    FULL extant and never re-applies the projection.'''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.b14.projbypass@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      // A single lifecycle bucket carrying a projected (exposed) field and a
      // hidden field; the projection `{ label }` must drop `secret`.
      records: {
        $key: "id"
        $bucket: { $from: ".starts", $until: ".ends" }
        id: "text"
        label: "text"
        secret: "text"
        starts: "timestamp"
        ends: "timestamp"
      }
      $public: {
        // Control: a bare temporal read in full shape shows both fields, so the
        // hidden field is present in the extant and only the projection hides it.
        read_full: {
          $params: { t: "timestamp" }
          $view: ".records.$at(@t) { label, secret }"
        }
        // Control: a plain projection (no temporal selector) reshapes to `label`
        // only through the ordinary Project path, never touching working_set.
        read_plain_projected: {
          $view: ".records { label }"
        }
        // Bug: a projected temporal read must reshape the active rows to `{ label }`.
        // working_set discards the projected base and returns the full extant,
        // leaking the hidden `secret` field.
        read_projected_temporal: {
          $params: { t: "timestamp" }
          $view: ".records { label }.$at(@t)"
        }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      // Both rows share the interval [2025-06-01T00:00:00Z, 2027-01-01T00:00:00Z),
      // so both are active at the 2026-01-01 clock and at the 2026-03-15 read.
      records: {
        r1: { label: "alpha", secret: "hush-1", starts: "1748736000000000", ends: "1798761600000000" }
        r2: { label: "beta", secret: "hush-2", starts: "1748736000000000", ends: "1798761600000000" }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    // Control: bare temporal at 2026-03-15T00:00:00Z shows both fields of both rows,
    // proving `secret` is present in the extant that the projection must drop.
    { watch: "public.read_full", args: { t: "1773532800000000" }, id: "w1"
      expect_init: {
        value: { $unordered: [
          { label: "alpha", secret: "hush-1" }
          { label: "beta", secret: "hush-2" }
        ] }
      } }

    // Control: the plain projection reshapes to `label` only, proving the projection
    // works in the ordinary evaluation path (exact object match: no `secret`).
    { watch: "public.read_plain_projected", id: "w2"
      expect_init: {
        value: { $unordered: [
          { label: "alpha" }
          { label: "beta" }
        ] }
      } }

    // Bug: the projected temporal read must reshape each active row to `{ label }`,
    // hiding `secret`. The runtime leaks `secret` because working_set ranges the
    // selector over the full extant and drops the projection (§7.1/§14.1).
    { watch: "public.read_projected_temporal", args: { t: "1773532800000000" }, id: "w3"
      expect_init: {
        value: { $unordered: [
          { label: "alpha" }
          { label: "beta" }
        ] }
      } }
  ]
}
